      <p>ASIACRYPT. Provides the most detailed gate-level resource estimates for running Shor's algorithm on prime-field elliptic curves, including optimized modular arithmetic circuits and concrete qubit/Toffoli counts for 256-bit curves.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1905.09749" target="_blank">Gidney & Ekerå (2021) - "How to factor 2048 bit RSA integers in 8 hours using 20 million noisy qubits"</a>
      <p>Quantum. Establishes the current benchmark for large-scale cryptanalytic quantum computing, introducing optimized surface-code compilation with windowed arithmetic and magic state distillation factories.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2001.09580" target="_blank">Häner et al. (2020) - "Improved quantum circuits for elliptic curve discrete logarithms"</a>
      <p>Quantum Science and Technology. Presents improved reversible arithmetic circuits for ECDLP, reducing both qubit count and circuit depth through optimized modular inversion and point addition subroutines.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.08648" target="_blank">Xu et al. (2024) - "Constant-overhead fault-tolerant quantum computation with reconfigurable atom arrays"</a>
      <p>Nature Physics. Directly supports the "Next-Gen Error Correction" agenda by demonstrating how quantum Low-Density Parity-Check (qLDPC) codes mapped to dynamically reconfigurable hardware can achieve fault tolerance with constant overhead, bypassing the unsustainable physical qubit scaling of 2D surface codes.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.06993" target="_blank">BAQIS Team et al. (2025) - "QSteed: A Resource-Virtualized and Hardware-Aware Quantum Compilation Framework"</a>
      <p>arXiv. Highlights the critical necessity of "Hardware-Aware Compilers" by proposing a deep-stack compilation framework that dynamically maps algorithmic requirements to the specific topology, noise characteristics, and cross-talk metrics of physical sub-regions on a QPU.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2208.01215" target="_blank">Liang et al. (2022) - "NAPA: Intermediate-level Variational Native-pulse Ansatz for Variational Quantum Algorithms"</a>
      <p>IEEE TCAD. Substantiates the "Direct-to-Pulse Synthesis" approach, showing that replacing abstracted gate compilations with direct hardware-level microwave pulse generation (native-pulse ansatz) heavily reduces circuit execution latency and mitigates calibration redundancy.</p>
    </li>
  </ReferenceList>
  </PageLayout>
</Base>
